# Spring Boot & Java 25 Standards

## Project Structure

Follow this layout under `backend/reservation-code/src/main/java/com/devsenior/angelmon091/reservation_code/`:

```
reservation_code/
├── BackendReservasApplication.java     # Main application
├── config/                             # @Configuration beans (security, CORS, etc.)
├── controller/                         # REST @RestController
├── service/                            # Business logic @Service
├── repository/                         # Spring Data JPA @Repository
├── entity/                             # JPA @Entity (domain model)
├── dto/                                # Request/Response records
│   ├── request/                        # Incoming DTOs
│   └── response/                       # Outgoing DTOs
├── exception/                          # Global @ControllerAdvice, custom exceptions
└── util/                               # Shared utilities (optional)
```

Tests mirror `src/main/java` under `src/test/java` with same package.

## Naming (English Only)

- **Classes, interfaces, records**: PascalCase (e.g. `ReservationService`, `CreateReservationRequest`).
- **Methods and attributes**: camelCase (e.g. `findById`, `customerName`).
- **Constants**: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (e.g. `MAX_PAGE_SIZE`).
- All identifiers must be in English.

## Javadoc for Public API

Every **public** method (controllers, services, repositories if custom) must have Javadoc:

```java
/**
 * Finds a reservation by its unique identifier.
 *
 * @param id the reservation ID (must not be null)
 * @return the reservation if found
 * @throws EntityNotFoundException if no reservation exists for the given id
 */
public Optional<Reservation> findById(UUID id) {
    return repository.findById(id);
}
```

Include `@param`, `@return`, and `@throws` when applicable. Keep descriptions concise and in English.

## DTOs as Java Records

Use **records** for all DTOs (request/response). Prefer immutability and validation.

```java
// dto/request/CreateReservationRequest.java
package com.devsenior.angelmon091.reservation_code.dto.request;

import jakarta.validation.constraints.NotNull;
import jakarta.validation.constraints.Future;

/**
 * Request body for creating a new reservation.
 */
public record CreateReservationRequest(
    @NotNull String customerName,
    @NotNull @Future java.time.Instant startTime,
    @NotNull java.util.UUID resourceId
) {}
```

```java
// dto/response/ReservationResponse.java
package com.devsenior.angelmon091.reservation_code.dto.response;

import java.time.Instant;
import java.util.UUID;

/**
 * Response payload for a single reservation.
 */
public record ReservationResponse(
    UUID id,
    String customerName,
    Instant startTime,
    UUID resourceId,
    String status
) {}
```

- Place request DTOs in `dto.request`, response DTOs in `dto.response`.
- Document the record’s purpose with a short Javadoc above the record.

## Java 25 Practices

- **Records**: Use for DTOs and small value types; avoid mutable DTOs.
- **Pattern matching**: Prefer `instanceof` pattern and switch pattern matching where it simplifies code.
- **Sealed types** (if applicable): Use for restricted hierarchies (e.g. result/error types).
- **Text blocks**: Use `"""..."""` for multi-line strings (SQL snippets, JSON examples in tests).
- **var**: Use only when the type is obvious from the right-hand side; keep readability.
- Prefer `Optional` for optional returns; avoid null for public API when possible.

## Spring Boot Conventions

- **Controllers**: Thin layer; validate input with `@Valid`, return DTOs, delegate to services. Document each endpoint (Javadoc or OpenAPI).
- **Services**: `@Transactional` at service layer where a single transaction is needed; use read-only transactions for queries when appropriate.
- **Repositories**: Prefer Spring Data JPA method names or `@Query`; keep custom logic in services.
- **Entities**: Use `@Entity` in `entity/`; avoid exposing entities in REST API—map to DTOs.
- **Exceptions**: Use `@ControllerAdvice` and custom exceptions in `exception/`; return consistent error payloads (e.g. `ErrorResponse` record).
- **Configuration**: Externalize environment-specific values to `application.properties` / `application-*.properties`; use `@ConfigurationProperties` for grouped config.

## Checklist

- [ ] All names (classes, methods, attributes) in English.
- [ ] Every public method has Javadoc with `@param` / `@return` / `@throws` as needed.
- [ ] DTOs are Java records in `dto.request` and `dto.response`.
- [ ] New code follows the defined package structure.
- [ ] Controllers return DTOs; services work with entities and DTOs as appropriate.
